Today, the House passed a resolution honoring the life and legacy of Charlie Kirk. He was a fearless defender of freedom, a devoted follower of Christ, and an extraordinary influence on the conservative movement and younger generations.

His tragic assassination stands as one of the darkest acts of political violence in my lifetime. We must come together to end this violence and honor the profound, lasting impact Charlie made on our country.

This week, the House passed two bills to advance President Trump’s mission of making D.C. safer:

✅ H.R. 4922 – DC CRIMES Act: Lowers the age of all “youth offenders” from 24 to 18, so adults are tried as adults.
✅ H.R. 5140 – DC Juvenile Sentencing Reform Act: Lowers age to 14 for trying violent juvenile defendants as adults.

These bills ensure no crime goes ignored and every offender is held accountable, keeping D.C. safer for all.

Today we honor all who have served in the United States Air Force. Since 1947, they have stood as a symbol of American strength, unmatched in skill, power, and dedication.

From protecting our skies to advancing aviation and technology, their service keeps our nation safe and our freedoms secure. We are forever grateful.

🚨 WIN: @WaysandMeansGOP just unanimously passed my bipartisan Fair and Accountable IRS Reviews Act through committee.

Taxpayers deserve safeguards against unjust IRS penalties. My bill restores accountability by requiring direct supervisor approval before penalties are assessed.

Protecting taxpayers → Restoring integrity.

On September 17, 1787, the Constitution was signed, laying the foundation for our great nation. It enshrined the principles of liberty, limited government, and individual rights that still define America today.

These ideals are not just words on paper; they are the safeguards of our freedom. And every day, they are tested. That’s why we must remain vigilant, standing firm in defense of the Constitution and the values that make our country strong.

I reintroduced Dillon’s Law, bipartisan legislation to save lives in schools across the country.

In 2014, Dillon Mueller of Mishicot, Wisconsin, was stung by a bee and suffered a fatal anaphylactic reaction. His life was tragically cut short at just 18 years old.

This bill would expand who is allowed to administer epinephrine in schools, ensuring that trained individuals can act quickly in emergencies and prevent tragedies like Dillon’s.

Thank you @RepDebDingell for co-leading this life-saving legislation.
https://t.co/jXDEZddMmN
